#!/usr/bin/env python3
"""
snappersend — Snapper-native Btrfs send/receive replication with a parent tree
==============================================================================

Replicates Snapper-created Btrfs snapshots from a SOURCE host to a DESTINATION
host over SSH via:

    btrfs send [-p PARENT] CLONE | [mbuffer |] ssh DEST "sudo btrfs receive DST"

It does NOT reimplement the Btrfs stream format or the network — btrfs does the
filesystem + stream work, ssh does the (encrypted) network, snappersend does the
bookkeeping. It does NOT create snapshots either: it assumes Snapper is installed
and taking timeline snapshots on the source (a `.snapshots` dir under each
configured subvolume). Two design choices are the heart of it:

TWO DESIGN CHOICES (and why)
----------------------------
1. WYSIWYG retention. The destination's retention is PURE GFS — what you configure
   is what you get, no "source-backed superset" that silently holds more than the
   config implies — with exactly ONE documented exception: the pinned incremental
   parent (the most recent snapshot is always kept as the next incremental's base).

2. Gaps do not force full sends. snappersend keeps its OWN parent clones in a
   private tree, immune to Snapper retention, so incrementals survive arbitrary gaps
   even when Snapper has pruned the original snapshot the send was based on.

THE PARENT-PRESERVATION TREE (the central mechanism)
----------------------------------------------------
On the SOURCE, snappersend keeps a private tree of read-only clones of the
snapshots it has successfully sent — one set per replicated subvolume, at
`<parent_tree_base>/<subvol>/` (default /.snappersend/<subvol>/). A clone is made
with `btrfs subvolume snapshot -r`: it shares extents via reflink (near-zero space)
but is an INDEPENDENT subvolume, so deleting Snapper's original does not touch it.
That is what decouples the parent's lifetime from Snapper retention.

WE SEND THE CLONE, NOT THE SNAPPER SNAPSHOT. This is the crux and was validated on
real btrfs before writing this: a `btrfs subvolume snapshot` gets a NEW uuid, so if
we sent Snapper's snapshot and kept a clone as the parent, the destination would
correlate on the snapshot's uuid while our retained parent carried the clone's uuid
— they would not match next run, breaking the chain. By sending the clone itself,
the destination's `received_uuid` equals the clone's uuid, so the clone we keep IS
the thing the destination correlates with. `btrfs send -p` between two clones of
different Snapper snapshots works because it simply diffs two read-only subvolumes
that share extents (proven: a 3-line incremental vs a full send, snapper original
deleted, still produced a correct receive).

THE PROMOTE-ON-CONFIRMED-SEND INVARIANT (the whole safety story)
---------------------------------------------------------------
The parent tree must only ever retain clones CONFIRMED landed on the destination.
Per run, per subvol:

  1. List existing clones = prior confirmed-sent states (untouched from prior runs).
  2. Choose the parent: the NEWEST clone that correlates with a destination
     snapshot (proves it is a valid base the destination still holds). None -> full.
  3. If Snapper's current newest is already represented by a correlating clone,
     there is nothing to send (idempotent re-run); go straight to retention.
  4. Otherwise stage a clone of Snapper's newest and send it, `-p <parent clone>`.
  5. On a VERIFIED-GOOD receive: keep the staged clone and prune clones beyond
     `parent_keep`. The tree advances ONLY here.
  6. On send/receive failure: DELETE the staged clone — the tree returns to exactly
     its prior state (old parent stays). Next run retries off the same parent.

Consequences honoured here:
  * Long gap / holiday: every failed run leaves the parent frozen and still
    correlating with the destination's newest, so on return the incremental works
    off the preserved clone — no full send. (The primary scenario this exists for.)
  * Divergence (no clone correlates: first run, or destination snapshot deleted/
    altered): full send, logged LOUDLY at INFO, parent tree reseeded on success.
  * Crash between send-OK and prune: the staged clone is already in the tree and the
    destination already has it, so next run simply continues off it. The invariant
    guarantees the parent is never AHEAD of the destination; stale-behind is
    recoverable, ahead is the corruption trap — we always stay on the safe side.

SEND MODEL: NEWEST-ONLY, NOT CATCH-UP
-------------------------------------
Each run sends ONLY Snapper's current newest snapshot, parented off its preserved
clone. It does not enumerate and ship every missing source snapshot. So the
destination is a SAMPLE at snappersend's run cadence, not a faithful copy of every
Snapper snapshot — by design, and what lets retention be WYSIWYG with no tombstones
(the send path never looks backward, so there is no re-send-of-pruned problem).

BTRFS CORRECTNESS RULES (proven on real btrfs; distilled from btrbk)
--------------------------------------------------------------------
(1) VALID RECEIVED SUBVOLUME: a clean receive is `readonly == true` AND
    `received_uuid` is set; a garbled one is writable with `received_uuid == '-'`.
    Every receive is verified; a garble is deleted and the run treated as failed.
(2) CORRELATION BY UUID (never by number): a == b when `a.uuid == b.received_uuid`
    OR `b.uuid == a.received_uuid` OR both `received_uuid` match. Both must be RO.
(3) RECEIVE-IN-PLACE: Snapper's subvol is literally named `snapshot`, so we receive
    into the final per-transfer directory directly — never `mv` a received RO subvol
    (copy fallback fails on the RO source) nor flip it RW (resets received_uuid).
(4) DESTINATION SNAPSHOTS STAY READ-ONLY — RO is what makes received_uuid a
    trustworthy base.
"""

